Pour the @water{240%ml} for the bulgur into a large #saucepan, stir in half of the @chicken stock paste{10%g} and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}. Stir the @dried cranberries{30%g} into the bulgur, pop a lid on the pan and remove from the heat.

Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a large #frying pan on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken thigh{260%g} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Fry until golden brown on the outside and cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While the chicken cooks, in a large #bowl, combine the @red wine vinegar{12%g}, @olive oil{1%tbsp} for the dressing and a good pinch of @?sugar{} (if you'd like). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Leave your dressing aside for now.

Once the chicken is cooked, stir in the @tomato puree{30%g} and @harissa paste{50%g} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and fry for a further ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @water{100%ml} for the sauce and the remaining @chicken stock paste{10%g}. Add a pinch of @?sugar{} (if you'd like).

Stir and bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until slightly thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Once thickened, stir the @baby spinach{40%g} into the pan a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

When ready, fluff up the bulgur with a #fork. Spoon half of the dressing over the bulgur and stir through.

Toss the @baby leaf mix{20%g} through the remaining dressing.

Share the cranberry bulgur between your plates.

Spoon the harissa chicken and spinach over the top.

Serve the dressed baby leaf salad alongside. Enjoy!